WEBVTT

00:09.109 --> 00:11.111
♪♪

00:11.144 --> 00:13.279
♪♪

00:15.315 --> 00:17.484
I have to slow down
and pay attention...

00:17.517 --> 00:18.518
[Dinging]

00:18.551 --> 00:20.020
Ding, ding, ding, ding, ding!

00:20.053 --> 00:22.188
...remember where
I've laid down roots,

00:22.222 --> 00:24.924
look back at the people
who got me here.

00:24.958 --> 00:27.427
One of the most prepared actors
I'd ever worked with.

00:27.460 --> 00:28.595
Really?
Yeah.

00:28.628 --> 00:30.130
And look ahead
to the unknown.

00:30.163 --> 00:31.698
Sometimes
it's just, like, one thing

00:31.731 --> 00:33.933
that changes the course
of the rest of your life.

00:34.701 --> 00:36.436
Reedus: Slow down.

00:36.469 --> 00:39.472
We have run out of gas
in the deserts of Joshua Tree.

00:39.506 --> 00:41.508
Reedus:
Los Angeles is my anchor.

00:41.541 --> 00:44.044
The desert is my release.

00:44.077 --> 00:46.112
♪♪

00:46.146 --> 00:56.122
♪♪

00:56.156 --> 01:01.327
♪♪

01:01.361 --> 01:04.130
Man: In the year since
the turn of the century,

01:04.164 --> 01:07.233
Los Angeles has grown
from a sleepy pueblo

01:07.267 --> 01:10.370
to a vast, seething,
metropolitan city.

01:10.403 --> 01:15.208
Fine buildings, huge stores,
busy citizens.

01:15.241 --> 01:18.011
[Horns honking]

01:18.044 --> 01:24.417
♪♪

01:24.451 --> 01:27.754
Reedus: When I was in my 20s,
I had a chip on my shoulder.

01:27.787 --> 01:29.355
I just assumed no one liked me,

01:29.389 --> 01:33.660
so I had this "You hate me,
I hate you first" attitude.

01:33.693 --> 01:37.831
For me, L.A. was a place
that accepted me for who I was.

01:37.864 --> 01:40.066
She was loud, raw,

01:40.100 --> 01:42.035
and bursting
with creative energy.

01:42.068 --> 01:44.170
She welcomed me with open arms

01:44.204 --> 01:46.506
at a time when I was just
trying to figure it all out.

01:46.539 --> 01:50.443
Hell, without her,
I don't know where I'd be today.

01:50.477 --> 01:51.845
♪♪

01:51.878 --> 01:53.847
Man: L.A. always
draws people to it.

01:53.880 --> 01:55.448
And it's got
a lot of hidden pockets.

01:55.482 --> 01:58.084
It's not a city you can visit
for a week or two and get.

01:58.118 --> 01:59.953
You gotta kinda live here.

01:59.986 --> 02:01.454
It's got like
an underbelly about it.

02:01.488 --> 02:02.388
You've got everything here.

02:02.422 --> 02:03.957
The mountains, the ocean,

02:03.990 --> 02:06.059
the city,
the people, the girls.

02:06.092 --> 02:08.061
Woman:
I think that creative people
just end up

02:08.094 --> 02:09.262
wanting to be here all the time

02:09.295 --> 02:12.899
because they just
get this feeling

02:12.932 --> 02:14.801
like they can
make anything out here.

02:14.834 --> 02:17.537
Man: It's a city
that attracts the dreamers.

02:17.570 --> 02:19.305
It's the only place
you can walk around

02:19.339 --> 02:21.407
and turn figments
of your imagination

02:21.441 --> 02:23.109
into cold, hard cash.

02:23.143 --> 02:24.978
♪♪

02:25.011 --> 02:29.983
Reedus: Last time I was here,
I was gone too fast.

02:30.016 --> 02:32.418
On this visit,
I'm slowing it down

02:32.452 --> 02:35.889
and hitting up a list of friends
in all corners of town

02:35.922 --> 02:38.057
before cruising east
to experience

02:38.091 --> 02:40.426
the unrivaled spirit
and community

02:40.460 --> 02:42.762
that surrounds Joshua Tree.

02:44.264 --> 02:45.231
♪♪

02:45.265 --> 02:47.500
But first I need to pay
a visit to my friend

02:47.534 --> 02:50.270
at one of the sickest
motorcycle shops in town.

02:50.303 --> 02:52.438
Yeah. What's up, dude?
<b></b>
What's up, dude?

02:52.472 --> 02:54.407
Nice to see you, man.
<b></b>
How you been?

02:54.440 --> 02:55.141
Dude, I been great.

02:55.175 --> 02:57.110
when's the last time
I saw you?

02:57.143 --> 02:59.679
Like a month ago?
Two months ago?
<b></b>
A couple months ago.

02:59.712 --> 03:01.447
Thanks for doing this.
<b></b>
How you been?

03:01.481 --> 03:03.183
I been good, I been good.
<b></b>
Traveling, riding,
enjoying life?

03:03.216 --> 03:05.151
All of it, all of it,
all of it.
Two wheels.

03:05.185 --> 03:07.287
♪♪

03:07.320 --> 03:10.256
Reedus:
With grease permanently caked
under his fingernails,

03:10.290 --> 03:14.928
Yaniv Evan, the mastermind
behind Powerplant motorcycles,

03:14.961 --> 03:17.497
has been building bikes
since he was a kid.

03:17.530 --> 03:20.934
Now he specializes
in custom throwback rides.

03:20.967 --> 03:22.268
Reedus: I feel like
when bikes go by,

03:22.302 --> 03:23.870
you can tell
if it's one of your bikes.

03:23.903 --> 03:25.438
The idea behind everything

03:25.471 --> 03:27.840
is to start with, like,
scrap piece of metal.

03:27.874 --> 03:29.842
Like, I --
I don't throw away anything.

03:29.876 --> 03:31.778
Like -- like this little ring,
for instance.

03:31.811 --> 03:34.314
I have oven parts
that I've found that
were really beautiful

03:34.347 --> 03:36.049
that I would attach
on some of my bikes.

03:36.082 --> 03:38.518
It's just raw materials
to start a bike with.

03:38.551 --> 03:40.620
This is where it,
like, starts.
<b></b>
You're an artist.

03:40.653 --> 03:42.021
What -- what do you --
what --

03:42.055 --> 03:43.489
What is it about L.A., like,
that makes your bikes --

03:43.523 --> 03:45.525
Like, I mean, you're
so successful here,

03:45.558 --> 03:46.960
like,
you know what I mean?

03:46.993 --> 03:49.295
Well, the motorcycle scene to me
is like fashion.

03:49.329 --> 03:50.797
You can't --
like, you can't be

03:50.830 --> 03:52.465
rocking the same look
for three years.

03:52.498 --> 03:53.166
You gotta change it.

03:53.199 --> 03:54.968
Like,
those bikes you can see,

03:55.001 --> 03:56.302
"oh, that was built
in the '90s or late 2000s."

03:56.336 --> 03:59.405
Like, I can tell
the era of the bikes,

03:59.439 --> 04:01.140
and you can't be,
like, half-assing it.
<b></b>
Right.

04:01.174 --> 04:02.809
You can't have one foot in
something that you're doing.

04:02.842 --> 04:04.177
You're gotta go
balls to the wall.

04:04.210 --> 04:05.311
This is what
we're doing now.

04:05.345 --> 04:06.312
We're building bikes
from scratch.

04:06.346 --> 04:10.650
♪♪
<b></b>
[Engine revs]

04:10.683 --> 04:12.652
♪♪

04:12.685 --> 04:18.524
♪♪
<b></b>
[Engine revs]

04:18.558 --> 04:22.195
Evan: These are the shop
hang-around dudes.

04:22.228 --> 04:23.763
Evan: No, actually,
they work here.

04:23.796 --> 04:25.498
-This is Cole.
-Yeah, dude.

04:25.531 --> 04:27.066
Cole: Nice to meet you.
<b></b>
Nice to meet you, man.
I'm Norman.

04:27.100 --> 04:28.434
And you're a stunt dude,
right?

04:28.468 --> 04:30.169
Yeah, that's --
that's what I do --

04:30.203 --> 04:32.272
wheelies, burnouts,
jump 'em like Evel Knievel.

04:32.305 --> 04:33.673
And how do you guys
know each other?

04:33.706 --> 04:37.010
I rode my bike
across the country, my FXR,

04:37.043 --> 04:39.545
and I broke down
pretty much pulling in here.

04:39.579 --> 04:42.015
And, uh, it was just --
actually the day

04:42.048 --> 04:44.450
one of his good friends
had passed away,

04:44.484 --> 04:45.385
so it was kind of weird.

04:45.418 --> 04:47.520
Evan: But -- but my friend
that passed away

04:47.553 --> 04:49.956
was passed away
'cause he was doing a wheelie,

04:49.989 --> 04:53.192
and a lady slammed her brakes
in front of him,

04:53.226 --> 04:56.062
and he --
he instantly hit her,

04:56.095 --> 04:57.697
and, uh, he -- he died.

04:57.730 --> 05:00.366
And the morning that he died
was a Sunday morning,

05:00.400 --> 05:03.536
and this freak shows up with
a broken exhaust on his bike.

05:03.569 --> 05:05.772
And I'm, like,
"this is not the day."

05:05.805 --> 05:07.273
I'm --
I'm, like, in tears,

05:07.307 --> 05:09.208
and we're sad,
everyone's quiet.

05:09.242 --> 05:10.476
I just felt bad.
I'm like, "you know what?

05:10.510 --> 05:11.911
I've gotta get my mind
off this thing,

05:11.944 --> 05:13.479
so bring your bike here."

05:13.513 --> 05:15.381
We ended up doing a whole day
surgery on his motor...

05:15.415 --> 05:17.216
It was a nightmare.
<b></b>
And got him on the road,

05:17.250 --> 05:19.252
but, we kind of, like,
during the time he was there,

05:19.285 --> 05:21.654
he's, you know,
showing off the bikes

05:21.688 --> 05:22.922
doing wheelies here.

05:22.955 --> 05:24.123
And I really respect guys
who can ride.

05:24.157 --> 05:25.391
Like, that's one thing.

05:25.425 --> 05:26.559
Like, I don't care
about anything.

05:26.592 --> 05:28.061
You can be
the biggest scum bag.

05:28.094 --> 05:30.463
You ride a bike
like the way he rides it,

05:30.496 --> 05:32.098
he's not a scum bag.

05:32.131 --> 05:33.566
[Laughs] Thanks, man,
I appreciate that.

05:33.599 --> 05:35.301
But if -- if he was,
I'd still respect him

05:35.335 --> 05:36.736
'cause the way
he rides a bike.

05:36.769 --> 05:38.071
Reedus: Respect.

05:38.104 --> 05:40.473
A quality decreed
to those who earn it,

05:40.506 --> 05:45.144
regardless of race, color,
or even if you're a scum bag.

05:45.178 --> 05:48.114
I don't know what I did
to earn Yaniv's respect,

05:48.147 --> 05:49.615
but he's letting me
ride one of his bikes

05:49.649 --> 05:50.983
to his favorite lookout.

05:51.017 --> 05:54.620
I'm not gonna
pass that chance up.

05:54.654 --> 05:56.422
♪♪

05:56.456 --> 05:58.624
-Yeah, buddy.
-This party's dope, dude.

05:58.658 --> 05:59.792
Reedus: Yeah.

05:59.826 --> 06:01.994
[Laughs]
Loving this bike, bro.

06:02.028 --> 06:03.196
Yeah.

06:03.229 --> 06:05.798
Welcome to L.A., mother (bleep)

06:05.832 --> 06:11.804
♪♪

06:11.838 --> 06:13.773
Whoo!

06:13.806 --> 06:15.108
[Spelljammer's "Meadow" plays]

06:15.141 --> 06:22.281
♪ You wanted to just this once
be free ♪

06:22.315 --> 06:29.355
♪ You wanted to hear these words
from me ♪

06:29.389 --> 06:35.495
♪ I know that my past
is just down the line ♪

06:35.528 --> 06:37.663
Evan: This is a good little
secret spot

06:37.697 --> 06:38.998
we come up to over here.

06:39.031 --> 06:42.135
Like, when things are harsh
at the shop,

06:42.168 --> 06:44.871
We come up here
and take a break for 5 minutes,

06:44.904 --> 06:46.906
do a little canyon riding,

06:46.939 --> 06:48.307
and go back to work.

06:48.341 --> 06:50.476
It's a good place
to bring a girl, too.

06:50.510 --> 06:53.813
Reedus: [Laughs]

06:53.846 --> 06:56.149
♪♪

06:56.182 --> 06:58.184
-There we go.
-Yeah, look at that.

06:58.217 --> 07:00.319
Beautiful view.
-Holy (bleep).

07:00.353 --> 07:02.522
That's something else.
-Yeah, this is cool up here.

07:02.555 --> 07:04.056
Reedus:
Yaniv, hat's off to you

07:04.090 --> 07:05.758
for building
these badass bikes, dude.

07:05.792 --> 07:06.726
I love it.

07:06.759 --> 07:09.595
♪♪

07:09.629 --> 07:11.497
Dude, this is awesome.

07:11.531 --> 07:13.266
♪♪

07:13.299 --> 07:15.501
Hey, this is where
we park usually.

07:16.102 --> 07:18.371
[Grunts] Whoo!

07:18.404 --> 07:20.440
Man.
<b></b>
Loving your bike, man.

07:20.473 --> 07:21.340
What a ride.

07:21.374 --> 07:23.342
Yeah, that was beautiful.

07:23.376 --> 07:25.178
That is a beast.
That's -- that's so powerful,

07:25.211 --> 07:26.712
I mean, it's great.
<b></b>
Dude, you looked good.

07:26.746 --> 07:28.381
I was looking in the back,
and we looked like a --

07:28.414 --> 07:29.749
like a stampede of buffalo.

07:29.782 --> 07:31.517
Evan: It's like
the best of both worlds --

07:31.551 --> 07:33.186
The motor from, like,
the newer bikes,

07:33.219 --> 07:34.854
but the frame -- this frame
they stopped making,

07:34.887 --> 07:36.689
so it wasn't really a Harley
when it came out.

07:36.722 --> 07:38.424
It was more like
a Japanese bike.

07:38.458 --> 07:39.759
So I'm glad you got
to get on one.

07:39.792 --> 07:41.294
Reedus: That's great, dude.
I loved it.

07:41.327 --> 07:42.428
Thank you, man.
Yeah.

07:42.462 --> 07:43.896
Cole:
The only time I feel free

07:43.930 --> 07:45.298
is on a motorcycle.

07:45.331 --> 07:46.966
I don't think about
any other bull (bleep).

07:46.999 --> 07:48.401
Just, like, mind's clear.
<b></b>
Yeah.

07:48.434 --> 07:50.369
This is a good --
good spot to get away,

07:50.403 --> 07:52.104
and just --
<b></b>
Throttle therapy, baby.

07:52.138 --> 07:53.539
Thanks for having us.

07:53.573 --> 07:54.607
Yeah, brother.

07:54.640 --> 07:58.878
♪♪

07:58.911 --> 08:02.548
Reedus:
You know, back in high school,
everybody had a punk band.

08:02.582 --> 08:04.217
Everyone thought
they were The Ramones,

08:04.250 --> 08:08.221
but spoiler alert,
they weren't.

08:08.254 --> 08:10.056
But everybody loved The Ramones
and their

08:10.089 --> 08:12.458
fight-the-establishment
attitude.

08:12.492 --> 08:14.327
So now that I'm back in L.A.,

08:14.360 --> 08:16.329
I finally made time
for the one place

08:16.362 --> 08:17.897
I've been dying to go to --

08:17.930 --> 08:19.098
the Ramones Ranch.

08:19.131 --> 08:21.767
♪♪

08:26.372 --> 08:28.808
[Mid-tempo music plays]

08:28.841 --> 08:31.010
Ramone: Shot of cream.

08:34.947 --> 08:36.449
-Cheers.
-Cheers.

08:36.482 --> 08:37.517
-Cheers
-Cheers, man.
<b></b>
["Opportunity" plays]

08:37.550 --> 08:39.085
♪ When it comes knockin' ♪

08:39.118 --> 08:40.920
♪ Open up the door
is what I say ♪
<b></b>
Mmm.

08:40.953 --> 08:42.255
That's perfect.

08:42.288 --> 08:43.823
That's exactly what I need.

08:43.856 --> 08:45.258
Oh, yeah.

08:45.291 --> 08:47.860
[Laughs]

08:47.894 --> 08:50.196
Reedus: Linda Ramone
and her boyfriend, J.D.,

08:50.229 --> 08:53.199
have a strange
and unconventional aesthetic.

08:53.232 --> 08:55.368
But for them, this is home.

08:55.401 --> 08:58.137
And it's where Johnny Ramone's
legacy lives on.

08:58.170 --> 08:59.939
Reedus:
We've never met, but...
<b></b>
No.

08:59.972 --> 09:01.807
...we have a ton
of mutual friends.
<b></b>
I know.

09:01.841 --> 09:03.709
And everybody loves you.
<b></b>
Oh, that's nice.

09:03.743 --> 09:05.511
Yeah.
<b></b>
Everybody loves you.
[Laughs]

09:05.545 --> 09:07.380
Everybody says
the best stuff about you.

09:07.413 --> 09:09.949
Of course, and I saw you put
a photo by Johnny's statue.

09:09.982 --> 09:12.018
Yeah, that's right.
<b></b>
And then I was, like,
who is that guy?

09:12.051 --> 09:14.453
I said to Fred, listen,
the other night...
Oh, yeah.

09:14.487 --> 09:16.289
...'cause he came over
for dinner.

09:16.322 --> 09:17.790
I go, "Do you know
that guy Norman?"

09:17.823 --> 09:20.293
And he goes, "Yeah, no,
he's really successful."

09:20.326 --> 09:21.794
I go,
"Oh, so he's not a bum."

09:21.827 --> 09:23.563
Fred's great.
<b></b>
And he goes,
"no, he's not a bum.

09:23.596 --> 09:25.298
He's really good."
[Laughs]
<b></b>
I'm kind of a bum,

09:25.331 --> 09:27.733
I'm kind of a bum.
<b></b>
I was, like, okay.

09:27.767 --> 09:29.502
♪♪

09:29.535 --> 09:32.705
Ramone: That painting
Dee Dee did of Johnny years ago,

09:32.738 --> 09:34.674
and DeeDee tried to sell it
to Johnny for $50,

09:34.707 --> 09:37.176
and Johnny's like,
"I'm not giving you
$50 for that."

09:37.209 --> 09:38.544
-[Laughs]
-And he goes,

09:38.578 --> 09:40.646
"And you put my guitar on
backwards to be a jerk."

09:40.680 --> 09:43.049
And Dee Dee goes, "No, no, no,
that's how I saw it."

09:43.082 --> 09:45.518
-Wow.
-[Laughs]

09:45.551 --> 09:47.486
Ramone: There's Johnny.

09:47.520 --> 09:49.522
I have Johnny's ashes
still.
Oh, wow.

09:49.555 --> 09:51.757
And then when I die,
J.D. buries me and Johnny,

09:51.791 --> 09:53.726
and when J.D. dies,
he buries himself.

09:53.759 --> 09:55.728
But we'll all go
into Hollywood forever.

09:55.761 --> 10:02.335
♪♪

10:02.368 --> 10:04.003
Reedus:
I love your paradise.

10:04.036 --> 10:05.004
This is it.
<b></b>
It's great.

10:05.037 --> 10:06.005
King: It's gorgeous.
Yeah.

10:06.038 --> 10:08.908
♪♪

10:08.941 --> 10:11.010
Ramone: There's really not
that much rock 'n' roll anymore

10:11.043 --> 10:12.178
That's the problem.

10:12.211 --> 10:14.347
I mean,
going out in New York

10:14.380 --> 10:16.349
was pretty amazing.

10:16.382 --> 10:18.551
I saw The Damned
and The Dead Boys

10:18.584 --> 10:20.386
a whole weekend
at CBGBs.

10:20.419 --> 10:21.854
You didn't know
it was a scene yet

10:21.887 --> 10:23.456
because you were just
going out.

10:23.489 --> 10:24.790
I was still really young.

10:24.824 --> 10:26.692
I was in high school
going out to see bands,

10:26.726 --> 10:29.128
but then the Ramones
took over the scene.

10:29.161 --> 10:31.731
And then it all
became more punk,

10:31.764 --> 10:34.467
and then the scene
kind of left,

10:34.500 --> 10:37.203
and new wave
started coming in.

10:37.236 --> 10:39.372
When new wave
sort of took over, like,

10:39.405 --> 10:41.040
was that --
was everybody upset?

10:41.073 --> 10:43.442
Oh, Johnny had a breakdown,
what do you mean?
Wow.

10:43.476 --> 10:44.744
Well,
'cause now you're, like,

10:44.777 --> 10:46.245
"well, what the hell
are you gonna do?"

10:46.278 --> 10:48.381
Punk never really
got played on the radio,

10:48.414 --> 10:49.782
so you kind of got ousted,

10:49.815 --> 10:53.285
and now they're starting
to play Blondie

10:53.319 --> 10:55.388
and Boy George and Visage

10:55.421 --> 10:57.890
and all these other bands
that are new wave,

10:57.923 --> 10:59.592
and they're not gonna
play punk.

10:59.625 --> 11:01.927
And you realize it,
you start getting more nervous,

11:01.961 --> 11:03.229
so that's what happened.

11:03.262 --> 11:04.597
And then
that's why the Ramones

11:04.630 --> 11:06.399
just kept playing and playing
and playing

11:06.432 --> 11:08.234
because there was no way
to retire.

11:08.267 --> 11:09.735
You had to play.

11:09.769 --> 11:13.172
♪♪

11:13.205 --> 11:14.940
So, where are you
going now?

11:14.974 --> 11:16.942
The guy that does
the special effects
for "Walking Dead,"

11:16.976 --> 11:18.277
his whole factory.

11:18.310 --> 11:19.812
And then Joshua Tree.
<b></b>
Okay.

11:19.845 --> 11:21.747
Which I've never
been there before.
All right.

11:21.781 --> 11:23.916
Thank you so much
for having me.

11:23.949 --> 11:24.850
You're so lovely.

11:24.884 --> 11:25.584
What a sweetheart.

11:25.618 --> 11:27.620
We'll see you very soon.
<b></b>
Yeah.

11:27.653 --> 11:29.689
[MXMS's "God" plays]
<b></b>
♪ Don't wanna be awake ♪

11:29.722 --> 11:33.092
♪ Don't wanna shut your eyes ♪

11:33.993 --> 11:36.429
Reedus: Seeing Linda,
paying my respects to Johnny,

11:36.462 --> 11:38.764
I'm flooded with memories
from when I lived here.

11:38.798 --> 11:41.600
L.A. is a place
where anything seems possible,

11:41.634 --> 11:43.602
and I'd like to think
that living here

11:43.636 --> 11:45.604
helped shape me into
who I am today.

11:45.638 --> 11:48.107
♪ Don't wanna fall apart ♪

11:48.140 --> 11:49.508
It's been a long day,

11:49.542 --> 11:51.043
but there's one person
who I can't miss seeing

11:51.077 --> 11:52.178
while I'm in town.

11:52.211 --> 11:54.814
Plus,
he'd kill me if I didn't.

11:54.847 --> 11:57.516
Or at least he'd make it
look like I had been killed.

11:57.550 --> 12:00.086
♪ You're still alive ♪

12:01.353 --> 12:02.455
♪♪

12:02.488 --> 12:03.456
Reedus: Oh, look at this.

12:03.489 --> 12:05.791
That's 1992, Irvine Meadows,

12:05.825 --> 12:07.827
Beastie Boys, Cypress Hill,
and House of Pain.

12:07.860 --> 12:10.463
-Arseface from "Preacher."
-Butthole face.

12:10.496 --> 12:12.164
Aah! So creepy.

12:12.198 --> 12:15.434
I could scare the (bleep)
out of people with this.
<b></b>
Take it.

12:16.702 --> 12:18.337
Reedus: Tell me if you want me
to slow down.

12:18.370 --> 12:20.072
You're all right,
as long as you feel good.

12:20.106 --> 12:22.875
♪♪

12:26.545 --> 12:30.683
♪♪

12:30.716 --> 12:32.685
♪♪

12:32.718 --> 12:34.320
Nicotero: Look at this.

12:34.353 --> 12:36.188
You're in my neck
of the woods now.
<b></b>
Hey, buddy.

12:36.222 --> 12:38.991
Hi, dude.
Hi, yeah.

12:39.024 --> 12:41.260
How are you?
<b></b>
I'm good. I'm good.

12:42.528 --> 12:44.296
Reedus:
Director, executive producer,

12:44.330 --> 12:46.265
special effects makeup designer,

12:46.298 --> 12:50.002
and one of my closest friends,
Greg Nicotero.

12:50.035 --> 12:51.837
He's an absolute legend,

12:51.871 --> 12:53.172
and you might recognize his work

12:53.205 --> 12:55.508
on a show called
"The Walking Dead."

12:55.541 --> 12:57.109
Dude, look at your office.
This is nuts.

12:57.143 --> 12:58.344
I know. I redid it.
Isn't it funny?

12:58.377 --> 12:59.512
Wait, hold on,
you gotta get --

12:59.545 --> 13:00.846
you gotta get
the full effect.

13:00.880 --> 13:02.114
This is what a giant --

13:02.148 --> 13:03.682
you know I'm a giant nerd,
of course.

13:03.716 --> 13:05.484
So this is the full effect
with the --

13:05.518 --> 13:06.986
Whoa!

13:07.019 --> 13:09.188
Is that a direct model
from something?
<b></b>
This is --

13:09.221 --> 13:11.524
this is a model
from "Lost in Space,"

13:11.557 --> 13:13.526
which was one of my favorite
shows when I was a kid.
<b></b>
Yeah.

13:13.559 --> 13:16.295
Nicotero:
So you know, it's, like,
"Danger, Will Robinson,"

13:16.328 --> 13:17.730
and you walk over here,
and you can, like,

13:17.763 --> 13:19.698
flip all the buttons on.

13:19.732 --> 13:23.369
And then, of course, you go from
this wacky '60s sci-fi

13:23.402 --> 13:26.071
to our little gallery
of, uh,

13:26.105 --> 13:27.339
of dead folks.

13:27.373 --> 13:29.642
[Suspenseful music plays]

13:29.675 --> 13:31.043
I recognize everyone.

13:31.076 --> 13:33.012
[Suspenseful music plays]

13:33.045 --> 13:35.714
And then we got the well walker.
We got the pets.
Yeah.

13:36.882 --> 13:38.150
It looks like it's real --

13:38.184 --> 13:39.785
like, feels like it's real.

13:41.053 --> 13:43.322
How did you get into this?

13:43.355 --> 13:45.691
You know, I just --
I grew up in Pittsburgh.

13:45.724 --> 13:48.227
I loved--
I loved horror movies,

13:48.260 --> 13:49.929
and it was just
one of those situations

13:49.962 --> 13:51.230
where I was getting ready

13:51.263 --> 13:53.232
to go off to school
to be a doctor,

13:53.265 --> 13:54.667
'cause my dad's a doctor,

13:54.700 --> 13:56.869
So I was pre-med...

13:56.902 --> 13:58.904
and I worked at a hospital
over the summer

13:58.938 --> 14:00.172
and sat in surgeries

14:00.206 --> 14:02.241
and watched them
cut people open.

14:02.274 --> 14:03.876
That must help
with all this.

14:03.909 --> 14:06.045
It totally did,
and that's how we got jobs.

14:06.078 --> 14:09.215
We got jobs because we did
"Dances with Wolves."

14:09.248 --> 14:10.716
The guy was, like,

14:10.749 --> 14:12.885
"God, you're p--
this stuff looks super real."

14:12.918 --> 14:14.587
So, um, the craziest thing

14:14.620 --> 14:17.256
is I remember going to
an operating room.

14:17.289 --> 14:19.425
One day I interned
with a surgeon.

14:19.458 --> 14:21.026
So I made the incision
in the body.

14:21.060 --> 14:22.862
It was like three seconds,

14:22.895 --> 14:24.530
and then the blood
started welling up.

14:24.563 --> 14:25.698
And they had this little
soldering iron,

14:25.731 --> 14:27.433
and they went,
"Sst, sst, sst."

14:27.466 --> 14:30.469
And they burned
all the blood vessels closed

14:30.502 --> 14:31.770
so it wouldn't bleed.

14:31.804 --> 14:34.440
And the weirdest thing
was the smell.

14:34.473 --> 14:37.943
I'll never forget that smell,
that burning-flesh smell.

14:37.977 --> 14:41.113
And every single time
we do gags in movies,

14:41.146 --> 14:43.482
it's like, I always think about,
"oh, well, the blood would --"

14:43.515 --> 14:44.817
you know,
when the heart's pumping,

14:44.850 --> 14:46.418
how long the blood
takes to come out.

14:46.452 --> 14:48.587
Do you ever get squeamish,
or no?

14:48.621 --> 14:49.655
Uh, no.

14:49.688 --> 14:59.465
[Rock music plays]

14:59.498 --> 15:00.633
There's Kevin working on...

15:00.666 --> 15:02.001
What's up, Kevin?
<b></b>
...a zombie head.

15:02.034 --> 15:03.269
Hey, how's it going, man?

15:03.302 --> 15:04.637
Nice to see you, man.
<b></b>
Good to see you.

15:04.670 --> 15:05.738
[Laughs]

15:05.771 --> 15:07.439
What are you making?

15:07.473 --> 15:10.175
A zombie crushed head --
A zombie smashed-in face.

15:10.209 --> 15:12.745
Wow, that's gross.
<b></b>
It's got all
the little dangly --

15:12.778 --> 15:15.347
Yeah.
It's a big sticky right now.
<b></b>
That's disgusting.

15:15.381 --> 15:17.750
Yeah,
it's pretty disgusting.
<b></b>
That's the trick is,

15:17.783 --> 15:20.319
every time you walk past
something like this on a table,

15:20.352 --> 15:22.321
you have to touch it.
<b></b>
Yeah, yeah.

15:22.354 --> 15:26.659
♪♪

15:26.692 --> 15:29.662
Reedus: Some of the stuff --
this is just like fun house.

15:29.695 --> 15:31.997
Who is this guy?
What does this do?

15:32.031 --> 15:33.299
Tell me about these guys.

15:33.332 --> 15:34.833
I thought
those were vaginas.

15:34.867 --> 15:36.835
What's up?
What's up, Greg?
<b></b>
It's a good look.

15:36.869 --> 15:38.671
I like the bigger nose
for you.
Yeah?

15:38.704 --> 15:41.140
What do you do with this?
<b></b>
When they rip it open

15:41.173 --> 15:43.342
they'll reveal...
<b></b>
That's awesome.

15:43.375 --> 15:45.711
...rib cage,
a little bit of muscle.

15:45.744 --> 15:48.047
-Arseface from "Preacher."
-Butthole face.

15:48.080 --> 15:49.682
-[Laughs]
-Nice.

15:49.715 --> 15:52.851
I could scare the (bleep)
out of people with this.
<b></b>
Take it.

15:53.819 --> 15:55.554
I like your style.
<b></b>
All right.

15:55.587 --> 15:56.855
[Laughs]

15:56.889 --> 15:59.358
♪♪

15:59.391 --> 16:01.927
Here's your figure.
Wow.

16:04.530 --> 16:06.799
This is weird.
I'm so used to --

16:06.832 --> 16:09.001
It is kind of wild.
<b></b>
It's so strange, yeah.

16:09.034 --> 16:10.536
To me, it's super weird.

16:11.070 --> 16:13.038
Here, hold on,
I'll take a picture of you

16:13.072 --> 16:14.373
taking a picture of you.

16:14.406 --> 16:16.241
♪♪

16:16.275 --> 16:17.543
Give me back my hat.

16:17.576 --> 16:19.511
Give me back my glasses.

16:20.079 --> 16:22.381
Wow, aah, it's so creepy.

16:22.414 --> 16:23.849
But first thing
we ever worked together

16:23.882 --> 16:25.718
was with John Carpenter.
<b></b>
Reedus: Yeah.

16:25.751 --> 16:27.987
It was
"The Masters of Horror."
<b></b>
Yeah, that's right, yeah.

16:28.020 --> 16:29.488
And he talked to you

16:29.521 --> 16:31.390
about hiring me
on "Walking Dead."

16:31.423 --> 16:33.392
Well, yeah,
so, you know, any time...

16:33.425 --> 16:36.095
Directors always like
to reach out to their friends

16:36.128 --> 16:37.896
and find out
what actors were like.

16:37.930 --> 16:39.832
And I remember calling John,
and he was, like,

16:39.865 --> 16:41.367
"What do you want?
What's up?

16:41.400 --> 16:43.235
Why are you bothering me?
What's happening?"

16:43.268 --> 16:44.703
And I said, "Hey, listen,
you know,

16:44.737 --> 16:46.338
we're thinking about
hiring Norman

16:46.372 --> 16:48.240
on 'Walking Dead.'"

16:48.273 --> 16:49.875
And he goes,

16:49.908 --> 16:52.244
"One of the most prepared actors
I'd ever worked with."

16:52.277 --> 16:53.345
Really?
Yeah.

16:53.379 --> 16:55.748
And then, of course, that was
all I ever heard of it.

16:55.781 --> 16:58.884
And then I get in the van,
and I'm in zombie makeup.

16:58.917 --> 17:01.787
It was my -- it was --
we were shooting episode 3,

17:01.820 --> 17:04.123
and you get in the van
next to me,

17:04.156 --> 17:05.557
not really
thinking about the fact

17:05.591 --> 17:07.259
that I'm wearing
zombie makeup.
Yeah.

17:07.292 --> 17:08.594
Like, "Hey, you're here."

17:08.627 --> 17:10.429
Yeah, you were my first zombie,
as well.

17:10.462 --> 17:12.231
And you were looking at me
going, "Yeah."

17:12.264 --> 17:13.766
Like,
you had no idea who I was.

17:13.799 --> 17:15.234
Yeah, yeah.

17:15.267 --> 17:16.368
And it was really funny

17:16.402 --> 17:17.936
'cause I was, like,
"It's Greg."

17:17.970 --> 17:19.538
And you're, like, no.

17:19.571 --> 17:21.106
Yeah, because you looked
so real.

17:21.140 --> 17:23.776
That was -- you were the first
talking zombie for me.

17:23.809 --> 17:28.814
That led to a good thing
over here, so.
Yeah.

17:28.847 --> 17:30.449
Show me more, show me more,
show me more, show me more.

17:30.482 --> 17:31.984
What else
do you want to see?
So much.

17:32.017 --> 17:34.119
Reedus: I never get sick of
looking at Greg's work.

17:34.153 --> 17:36.255
Nicotero: I'm sad
you're leaving already.
<b></b>
Reedus: I know.

17:36.288 --> 17:38.590
It feels like
you just got here.
<b></b>
I'll see you soon enough.

17:38.624 --> 17:40.893
But as Day 1 comes to a close,
I head out tonight,

17:40.926 --> 17:44.329
and I'll rest easy
in Hollywood.

17:44.363 --> 17:48.400
♪♪

17:48.434 --> 17:49.902
There's something beautiful

17:49.935 --> 17:52.171
about Los Angeles
just after sunrise.

17:52.204 --> 17:54.907
A calmness to it as it washes
the sleep from its eyes.

17:54.940 --> 17:58.911
Today I continue my ride east
towards Joshua Tree

17:58.944 --> 18:01.180
with a couple of stops
along the way,

18:01.213 --> 18:04.116
including a group ride
led by rapper Sen Dog

18:04.149 --> 18:08.187
and the motorcycle crew
the Cypress Hillbillies.

18:08.220 --> 18:09.588
But before I kick it into gear,

18:09.621 --> 18:11.490
I'm gonna meet up
with a close friend of mine

18:11.523 --> 18:13.959
who will join me
on my ride out of the city.

18:13.992 --> 18:15.661
Where is your shop
out here?

18:15.694 --> 18:17.262
I'm in
Alhambra, California.

18:17.296 --> 18:18.630
Oh, it's not that far.
<b></b>
No, no.

18:18.664 --> 18:20.299
I thought it was crazy far.
<b></b>
No, dude, no.

18:20.332 --> 18:23.669
I'm really close right there,
and it's a cool little shop.

18:23.702 --> 18:25.504
It's just me and my wife,
Fiona.

18:25.537 --> 18:27.506
And my kids
come after school.

18:27.539 --> 18:29.508
Your super-cute kids,
yeah.
Thanks, man.

18:29.541 --> 18:31.610
They're all right.
[Laughs]
[Laughs]

18:31.643 --> 18:33.545
Reedus: His grandfather
built railroads

18:33.579 --> 18:35.314
His father built cars.

18:35.347 --> 18:38.517
Chris Richardson's passion
for building innovative bikes

18:38.550 --> 18:40.719
runs deep within his veins.

18:40.752 --> 18:42.855
He owns L.A. Speed Shop

18:42.888 --> 18:44.857
and has an obsession
for detail,

18:44.890 --> 18:47.526
specializing in vintage choppers
and bobbers.

18:47.559 --> 18:51.029
One of my favorite bikes
that I own was built by him.

18:51.063 --> 18:52.498
♪♪

18:52.531 --> 18:54.133
I mean, how far is it
where we're going?

18:54.166 --> 18:56.034
What is it? Like, an hour,
hour and a half?

18:56.068 --> 18:58.570
I think
it's about 45 minutes.
<b></b>
To Palm Springs? Yeah.

18:58.604 --> 19:00.739
Probably with traffic,
it might be maybe two hours.

19:00.772 --> 19:03.976
Dude, your traffic out here
sucks!
<b></b>
Oh, it's crazy, man.

19:04.009 --> 19:05.477
I had a crash here once.

19:05.511 --> 19:08.547
This car jumped in
oncoming traffic lanes,

19:08.580 --> 19:10.816
and I could see this old lady
and this old man

19:10.849 --> 19:13.719
in the front seat
just doing like this...

19:13.752 --> 19:14.920
Yeah.
<b></b>
...as I hit the front

19:14.953 --> 19:16.421
and just kind of
flew over the car,

19:16.455 --> 19:18.323
and my bike
kind of did this.

19:18.357 --> 19:19.758
Oh, man.

19:19.791 --> 19:21.660
And I laid on the ground,
like, just twitching.

19:21.693 --> 19:23.228
And people were driving.

19:23.262 --> 19:24.563
Nobody stopped to help me,

19:24.596 --> 19:25.898
but people were
driving by going, "Sue 'em!"

19:25.931 --> 19:27.599
Like, ten people said,
"Sue 'em,"

19:27.633 --> 19:29.067
but nobody stopped
to help me.

19:29.101 --> 19:31.236
You know what,
and then I had to push my bike

19:31.270 --> 19:33.438
into the bushes
right there...
Yeah.

19:33.472 --> 19:35.007
...and walk
to a buddy's house

19:35.040 --> 19:37.676
and sort of do this on his sofa
for the rest of the day.

19:37.709 --> 19:39.678
Oh, dude.
Yeah, doing the tuna, right?

19:39.711 --> 19:41.580
It sucks. Yeah.
<b></b>
You're flopping around.

19:41.613 --> 19:43.916
Yeah.
<b></b>
[Horns honking]

19:43.949 --> 19:45.751
♪♪

19:45.784 --> 19:48.420
Riding in L.A.
is definitely treacherous.

19:48.453 --> 19:50.722
L.A. traffic has made me
move three times

19:50.756 --> 19:51.924
since I've been here.

19:51.957 --> 19:55.194
Traffic's pretty brutal,
100% brutal.

19:55.227 --> 19:57.229
Like, all the time.

19:57.262 --> 19:58.764
Man: You know, the 405,

19:58.797 --> 20:00.132
I do try
to stay away from that,

20:00.165 --> 20:02.935
and I take the city streets
as much I can.

20:02.968 --> 20:05.537
Every ten years,
I get in a wreck.

20:05.571 --> 20:06.772
I've survived 'em all.

20:06.805 --> 20:09.107
It's dangerous out there,
for sure.

20:09.141 --> 20:12.211
♪♪

20:12.244 --> 20:14.446
You ever heard of Cypress
Hillbillies before?

20:14.479 --> 20:15.614
Yeah, dude,
I have, actually.

20:15.647 --> 20:17.449
I'm excited to meet them
and hang out.

20:17.482 --> 20:18.984
I'm excited, too, yeah.
<b></b>
[Electric Citizen's
"Natural Law" plays]

20:19.017 --> 20:22.287
♪ You say a darker day
is coming ♪

20:22.321 --> 20:25.257
♪ To bring the laws
that nature laid ♪

20:25.290 --> 20:27.426
Reedus: We're gonna head east
to our next stop

20:27.459 --> 20:29.995
on the outskirts of the city.

20:30.028 --> 20:31.763
Where Sen Dog
and the Cypress Hillbillies

20:31.797 --> 20:35.968
wait for us at the end of
a quaint little cul-de-sac.

20:36.001 --> 20:37.636
Richardson:
Oh, right there, right there.

20:37.669 --> 20:40.839
Straight ahead.
<b></b>
Reedus: Yep.

20:40.872 --> 20:41.707
♪♪

20:41.740 --> 20:44.142
This is our main
pinball hall.
Wow.

20:44.176 --> 20:46.578
This one houses
over 700 pinball machines.

20:46.612 --> 20:48.947
The holy grail of
pinball machine collections.

20:48.981 --> 20:51.917
[Dinging]

20:58.824 --> 21:03.061
♪♪

21:03.095 --> 21:04.429
♪♪

21:04.463 --> 21:05.764
Reedus:
Sen Dog, the renowned member

21:05.797 --> 21:08.166
of the hip-hop group
Cypress Hill.

21:08.200 --> 21:09.668
He's an avid biker

21:09.701 --> 21:11.837
and an affiliate of
the exclusive motorcycle club

21:11.870 --> 21:13.705
The Cypress Hillbillies.

21:13.739 --> 21:15.540
They don't just let anyone
into the mix,

21:15.574 --> 21:17.242
but today,
they've made an exception

21:17.276 --> 21:19.311
to let me join them
on a group ride.

21:21.713 --> 21:23.882
Reedus: This bike is
a beast right there.
That's yours?

21:23.915 --> 21:25.450
That's mine.
That's Lucinda right there.

21:25.484 --> 21:26.718
Lucinda?
Yeah.

21:26.752 --> 21:28.387
That's a serious motorcycle
right there.

21:28.420 --> 21:31.223
Yeah, that's an '03
anniversary-edition Springer.

21:31.256 --> 21:33.058
Funny, I went to buy
that bike one day,

21:33.091 --> 21:35.727
and the dealer dude
didn't even look at me,
talk to me, or nothing.

21:35.761 --> 21:37.596
He just let me
look around and leave.

21:37.629 --> 21:38.930
so I went back
the next day like,

21:38.964 --> 21:40.632
"Damn it, I'm gonna get me
this motorcycle."

21:40.666 --> 21:42.567
So as I'm walking in,
the same dude that ignored me

21:42.601 --> 21:43.935
opened the door for me.

21:43.969 --> 21:45.437
He goes, "You're ready now,
aren't you, son?"

21:45.470 --> 21:48.307
Oh, he knew it.
<b></b>
I go, "Damn right, I am."

21:48.340 --> 21:50.375
I go, "that one right there."
<b></b>
Wow.

21:50.409 --> 21:52.377
I didn't really expect
to, you know,

21:52.411 --> 21:53.879
to love it
as much as I did.

21:53.912 --> 21:55.814
Not just the bike,
just the whole culture.

21:55.847 --> 21:57.416
Just the whole family
of people,

21:57.449 --> 21:58.784
that we all love
the same thing.

21:58.817 --> 22:00.919
So how long has your club
been around?

22:00.952 --> 22:02.721
We've been rolling
for seven years.

22:02.754 --> 22:05.324
Um, this year, it'll be our
eighth year in a few months.

22:05.357 --> 22:07.626
Before every ride,
we meet up here, you know,

22:07.659 --> 22:09.895
and get together and
make a game plan if it's
not already made,

22:09.928 --> 22:11.797
and after the ride, you know,
we also come back here

22:11.830 --> 22:13.765
and just, you know,
loosen out a little bit

22:13.799 --> 22:15.567
before everybody goes home.
<b></b>
Yeah. Yeah.

22:15.600 --> 22:17.736
We're still at it.
There's no other life, you know.

22:17.769 --> 22:21.673
♪♪

22:21.707 --> 22:23.442
Reedus:
Some of these photos over here.

